# NetSuite SuiteScript Rules

## Version and Module Pattern
- SuiteScript 2.x only â€” always include `@NApiVersion 2.x`
- AMD-style `define()`/`require()` modules â€” no CommonJS
- Always declare `@NScriptType` and `@NModuleScope`

```javascript
/**
 * @NApiVersion 2.x
 * @NScriptType Restlet
 * @NModuleScope SameAccount
 */
define(['N/search', 'N/error', 'N/log'], function(search, error, log) {
    // implementation
    return { get, post };
});
```

## File Naming
Use a **letter-first** prefix so Script IDs stay valid in NetSuite (IDs cannot start with a digit). Format: `m37m_{purpose}_{type}.js`

| Script Type | Example Filename |
|-------------|-----------------|
| RESTlet | `m37m_saved_search_restlet.js` |
| Scheduled Script | `m37m_update_inventory_scheduled.js` |
| User Event | `m37m_validate_order_userevent.js` |
| Suitelet | `m37m_coa_generator_suitelet.js` |
| Map/Reduce | `m37m_bulk_import_mapreducescript.js` |
| Client Script | `m37m_order_form_clientscript.js` |

## NetSuite Internal IDs
- Script IDs: `m37m_custom_{purpose}_{type}` â€” e.g. `m37m_custom_saved_search_restlet`
- Deployment IDs: `m37m_custom_{purpose}_{type}_{variant}` â€” e.g. `m37m_custom_saved_search_restlet_v1`

## Directory Naming (File Cabinet and repo)
- Lowercase with underscores: `saved_search_return/`, `coa_generator/`, `20x_build_calculator/`

## Required in Every Script
- JSDoc header documenting script type, deployment, parameters, and description
- `try/catch` in every entry-point function â€” never let an unhandled exception crash silently
- `log.debug`, `log.audit`, or `log.error` for all logging â€” never `console.log`
- No hardcoded values that should be script parameters or deployment configuration

```javascript
function get(requestParams) {
    try {
        log.debug({ title: 'get called', details: JSON.stringify(requestParams) });
        // implementation
        return results;
    } catch (e) {
        log.error({ title: 'get failed', details: e.message + '\n' + e.stack });
        throw e;
    }
}
```

## Governance Limits
- Be aware of script governance limits per script type (usage points)
- Minimize API calls â€” batch reads and writes where possible
- For large data sets, prefer Map/Reduce over Scheduled Script
- Test governance usage in sandbox; log governance consumed in scheduled scripts

## Authentication
- New integrations: **OAuth 2.0 only**
- TBA (Token-Based Authentication) is legacy â€” do not use for new integrations
- NetSuite 2027.1+: no new SOAP integrations permitted
- Existing TBA setups: document key generation in `keygen_notes.txt` per project folder

## Repository Structure
```
37m-netsuite-scripts/
  saved_search_return/
    m37m_saved_search_restlet.js
    keygen_notes.txt
  20x_build_calculator/
    m37m_20x_build_calculator_suitelet.js
  coa_generator/
    m37m_coa_generator_suitelet.js
  README.md
```

## Branch Naming
Format: `{type}/{initials}/{short-description}`
- `feature/cs/20x-build-calculator`
- `fix/bk/coa-pdf-alignment`
- `update/ms/saved-search-pagination`

## Deployment Process â€” Follow Exactly
1. Develop and test in **sandbox** â€” never in production
2. Check Script Execution Log (`Customization > Scripting > Script Execution Log`) for errors
3. Commit to GitHub, open PR targeting `develop` when the repo uses that flow
4. **Peer or self review** â€” do not deploy untested changes
5. Deploy to production per your runbook: File Cabinet upload, Script record, Deployment
6. Verify in production after deployment

## Validation Scripts
Scripts used in manufacturing, QC, or regulated processes require a validation plan (IQ/OQ/PQ) before production use. Coordinate with stakeholders and quality assurance before beginning development.
